# Astro Motion Framework - Full Reference

A simple, repeatable way to make Astro sites feel premium. For projects using Astro without React in the bulk of pages.

## Why motion matters

Motion is the single biggest "this looks expensive" lever on a website. Subtle reveal animations, considered hover states, content that arrives with intention - this is what separates a $20k site from a $2k site. Most Astro builds skip it because the obvious option (Framer Motion) doesn't fit, and rolling your own feels janky.

This framework picks one library (GSAP), one architecture (three layers), and one set of class-based conventions.

## The library: GSAP

GreenSock Animation Platform. Industry standard for nearly two decades.

- **Framework-agnostic** - works in vanilla `<script>` blocks inside `.astro` files. No React islands, no hydration boundary.
- **Reliable on iOS** - handles Chrome iOS and Safari iOS scroll quirks that break DIY IntersectionObserver implementations.
- **Free forever** - Webflow acquired GSAP in 2024 and made everything free, including SplitText, MorphSVG, DrawSVG, Flip, MotionPath. Use **3.13+** to get the all-free licence applied to plugins.
- **~40KB gzipped** for core + ScrollTrigger.
- **Massive ecosystem** - endless CodePen demos at gsap.com/showcase.

**Framer Motion is React-only.** It would force `.astro` components into React islands and ship React + ReactDOM purely to animate. Not worth it for a project that doesn't otherwise use React.

**Motion One** (~4KB) is valid for minimal needs but default to GSAP for anything beyond basic fades.

## File structure

```
src/
├── scripts/
│   └── motion.js        ← all animation logic
├── styles/
│   ├── globals.css      ← project's global stylesheet (Tailwind entry, tokens)
│   └── motion.css       ← reveal classes + reduced-motion handling
└── layouts/
    └── BaseLayout.astro ← loads GSAP + imports motion.js
```

Import `motion.css` from `globals.css` so it's part of the same CSS bundle.

## Order of operations on existing projects

Greenfield projects can skip ahead to the install. On any project that isn't greenfield, follow this sequence:

1. **Audit** existing motion (Step 0 in main rule)
2. **Cleanup** conflicting CSS animations as a discrete commit
3. **Install** GSAP, scaffold files, wire into `BaseLayout` and `globals.css`
4. **Layer 1 blanket pass** - apply `.reveal` to every eligible block in a single change
5. **Layer 2 patterns** - apply per-component, one at a time
6. **Layer 3 hero moments** - last, only when explicitly requested

Critically: don't compress steps 4 and 5 into one chat. Ship the blanket reveal first; iterate on hover patterns separately. If some blocks fade in and others don't, the site looks half-finished.

## Step 0 - Audit checklist

On any existing project, before scaffolding, check for:

1. **CSS hover animations on cards/buttons** that overlap with Layer 2 (`group-hover:scale-*`, `hover:translate-*`, `transition-transform duration-*` on cards)
2. **Orphaned `@theme` animation tokens** - keyframes defined but never referenced
3. **DIY `IntersectionObserver`** scroll reveals
4. **Existing animation libraries** (Motion One, AOS, Framer Motion, anime.js)

Report findings to the user before making changes. Cleanup is its own commit before installing GSAP.

## Functional UI state - leave alone

The framework governs **decorative motion** only. Functional UI state feedback is out of scope and must not be migrated or removed:

- `transition-colors`, `transition-opacity`, `transition-shadow` on hover/focus/active
- Focus rings (accessibility)
- Accordion / disclosure expand-collapse
- Modal / dialog / dropdown / popover open-close
- Switch / toggle / checkbox state
- Hamburger menu line-to-X transforms
- Mobile menu staggered item reveals (bespoke component state)
- Tiny indicator nudges (arrow `translate-x-0.5`, chevron rotate)

State feedback = keep, decorative = migrate.

## Three-layer architecture

### Layer 1 - Base reveals

Everything meaningful that scrolls into view fades up gently. One class, applied everywhere.

```html
<section class="reveal">...</section>
<h2 class="reveal">...</h2>
<img class="reveal" />
```

Implemented once using GSAP's `ScrollTrigger.batch()` in `motion.js`.

### Layer 2 - Component patterns

Reusable interactions per component type. Defined once in `motion.js`, applied via class.

### Layer 3 - Hero moments

One-off cinematic touches. Hand-written per instance.

## The `.reveal` class - application rules

**Apply to:**

- Section containers
- Headings (h1, h2, h3)
- Paragraphs of body copy
- Images and galleries
- Cards (project, testimonial, service)
- Stats and numbers
- Quote blocks

**Don't apply to:**

- Nav bars and headers (already visible)
- Footers
- Background decorations
- Anything inside a card that's already revealing

### Per-block rubric (use during the Layer 1 blanket pass)

- **Hero / intro blocks**: heading + sub + CTA, with incremental `reveal-delay-*` for cascade
- **Single-section content blocks**: apply to the section root - one fade-up per block
- **Grid / card blocks**: apply to each card, not the grid container - `ScrollTrigger.batch()` staggers automatically
- **Image + text blocks**: image and text get separate `.reveal`
- **Quote / stat / testimonial blocks**: apply to the element directly

### Stagger variants

```html
<h1 class="reveal">Heading</h1>
<p class="reveal reveal-delay-1">First paragraph</p>
<p class="reveal reveal-delay-2">Second paragraph</p>
<a class="reveal reveal-delay-3">CTA button</a>
```

Each `-delay-N` adds 150ms. Use `-1` through `-4` only.

### Direction variants

```html
<div class="reveal reveal-left">Slides in from left</div>
<div class="reveal reveal-right">Slides in from right</div>
<div class="reveal reveal-scale">Scales up from 95%</div>
```

Default `.reveal` fades up from 24px below.

## Pattern library (Layer 2)

- **`.project-card`** (or `.feature-card`, `.service-card`) - image scales to 1.05, card lifts 8px with subtle shadow on hover
- **`.btn-primary`** - scales to 1.03 with 0.2s ease on hover
- **`.btn-pulse`** - continuous scale loop (1.0 → 1.05 → 1.0) on 2s repeat. One per page max.
- **`.nav-link`** - underline draws left-to-right on hover
- **`.logo-intro`** - first-load entrance with `back.out` ease. **Always store a flag in `sessionStorage`** so it doesn't replay on every page navigation.
- **`.number-counter`** - count-up from 0 when scrolled into view

Pick **one** card-pattern name per project (`.project-card` OR `.feature-card` OR `.service-card`) and stick with it - don't mix conventions.

## Easing consistency

Before defining GSAP eases, check the project's existing CSS for shared easing curves. Most polished projects already have a signature `cubic-bezier` used across UI transitions (buttons, links, focus, etc.). Mirror that curve in `motion.js` via `CustomEase` so decorative motion feels of-a-piece with the rest of the UI.

Default to `power3.out` only if no existing convention exists.

## iOS hover safety

The Chrome iOS "double-tap" bug is a hover problem, not a library problem.

```css
@media (hover: hover) {
  /* All hover styles go here */
}
```

Use `:active` for mobile tap feedback. Add `touch-action: manipulation` to buttons/links.

## Accessibility - `prefers-reduced-motion`

```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .reveal {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: none;
    transition: none;
  }
}
```

```js
const prefersReducedMotion = window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)').matches;
if (!prefersReducedMotion) {
  // initialise GSAP animations
}
```

## Astro View Transitions

If the project uses `<ViewTransitions />` from `astro:transitions`, GSAP and ScrollTrigger must be re-initialised on `astro:page-load` rather than `DOMContentLoaded`. Otherwise reveals stop firing after the first soft-navigation.

```js
document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initMotion);

document.addEventListener('astro:before-swap', () => {
  ScrollTrigger.getAll().forEach((t) => t.kill());
});
```

## Where to find proven patterns

Don't write from scratch. Pull from:

### Osmo Supply - `osmo.supply`

Library of polished, copy-paste GSAP motion components. Freemium - most common patterns are free. First place to look for premium motion without iteration.

Workflow: browse → find pattern → copy code → paste into Cursor → "apply this to my project cards / hero / nav."

### Codrops - `tympanus.net/codrops`

Long-running animation tutorial site. Search "GSAP reveal" or "scroll animation."

### GSAP Showcase - `gsap.com/showcase`

Official directory of production sites built with GSAP. Filter by effect type.

### Reference video method

If you can point to a site whose motion you like: screen-record scrolling on phone, feed to Cursor: *"Look at the animation patterns in this video. Implement equivalent motion using GSAP. Match timing and easing as closely as you can."*

## Canonical first-use prompt

Paste this after referencing `@astro-motion-framework-reference.mdc` to introduce the framework to a project:

> *"Audit existing motion in this project per Step 0. Report findings, then in one pass: clean up conflicts, install GSAP, scaffold motion.js and motion.css, wire into BaseLayout and globals.css, and apply `.reveal` to every eligible block (Layer 1 blanket pass). Stop before any Layer 2 hover patterns - we'll do those one at a time."*

## Cursor workflow tips

**Do:**

- Reference existing motion.js: *"Add a new pattern to motion.js following the existing structure"*
- Point at Osmo/Codrops demos: *"Apply this pattern, keep implementation minimal, single file, no extra abstraction layers"*
- Be specific about timing: *"0.8s duration, ease 'power3.out', stagger 0.1s"*

**Don't:**

- Use vague prompts like "make it look nice" - produces bland defaults
- Scatter animation logic across components - keep it centralised in motion.js
- Mix CSS transitions with GSAP for the same element - pick one
- Start applying Layer 2 hovers before the Layer 1 blanket pass is shipped

## TL;DR

1. **Library**: GSAP 3.13+ (free, framework-agnostic, reliable on iOS)
2. **File**: `src/scripts/motion.js` + `src/styles/motion.css`
3. **Order**: audit → cleanup → install → blanket reveal → iterate Layer 2 → Layer 3 last
4. **Three layers**: base reveals (`class="reveal"`), pattern interactions, hero moments
5. **Don't touch**: functional UI state (focus, accordion, modals, switches, hamburger)
6. **Hover safely**: `@media (hover: hover) { }`
7. **Respect reduced motion**: wrap GSAP init in `matchMedia` check
8. **View Transitions**: re-init on `astro:page-load`, kill ScrollTriggers on `astro:before-swap`
9. **Match existing easing**: don't introduce a second easing language
10. **Don't write from scratch**: pull patterns from Osmo Supply, Codrops, GSAP showcase
11. **Reuse across projects**: copy `motion.js` and `motion.css` into every new Astro build
